83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
House Bill 4007
Introduced and printed pursuant to House Rule 12.00. Presession filed (at the request of House Interim Committee
on Transportation)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure as introduced. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability
standards.
Digest: The Act defines what a “powered micromobility device” is. It also combines the laws for
kids under 16, making it clear that they must wear helmets when riding bikes, e-bikes, e-scooters
and some other vehicles. Changes age a kid must be to use different classes of e-bikes and other
types of vehicles. Says a store may not sell a vehicle that looks like an e-bike if it is not an e-bike
by state law. The Act tells ODOT to make a new pilot program and let trucks haul more milk on
certain routes. The Act tells ODOT to report on the results of the pilot program. (Flesch Readability
Score: 70.7).
Defines “powered micromobility device” for the vehicle code.
Consolidates and makes uniform standards for wearing protective headgear for children under
16 years of age when riding or using a bicycle, electric assisted bicycle, motor assisted scooter,
powered micromobility device and certain nonmotorized vehicles.
Lowers the age requirement to operate a Class 1 electric assisted bicycle. Provides that there
is no minimum age requirement to operate a Class 1 or Class 2 electric assisted bicycle if the person
is participating in a bicycle safety program.
Lowers age requirement to operate motor assisted scooter.
Creates offense of improper sale or lease of a vehicle. Punishes by maximum fine of $250.
Creates offense of selling an impostor vehicle. Punishes by maximum fine of $250.
Directs the Department of Transportation to establish a five-year pilot program that allows ve-
hicles to haul fluid milk products with a loaded weight of not more than 129,000 pounds on routes
approved by the department. Directs the department to conduct a study and prepare a report on the
results of the pilot program.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to transportation; creating new provisions; amending ORS 153.633, 153.645, 153.650, 153.660,
3 646.608, 801.348, 803.030, 803.305, 806.020, 807.020, 811.050, 811.440, 814.484, 814.486, 814.487,
4 814.489, 814.512, 815.052 and 815.281; and repealing ORS 814.485, 814.487, 814.488, 814.534 and
5 814.600.
6 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
7
8 POWERED MICROMOBILITY DEVICES AND MOTOR ASSISTED SCOOTERS
9
10 SECTION 1. Sections 2, 3 and 4 of this 2026 Act are added to and made a part of the
11 Oregon Vehicle Code.
12 SECTION 2. Definition of “powered micromobility device.” (1) “Powered micromobility
13 device” means a vehicle that:
14 (a) Is designed to transport a person;
15 (b) Has a propulsion system;
16 (c) Has a maximum speed of 28 miles per hour; and
17 (d) Has an unloaded weight of less than 100 pounds.
18 (2) “Powered micromobility device” does not include:
19 (a) Devices exclusively powered by human power; or
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 255

HB 4007
1 (b) The following devices or vehicles:
2 (A) Electric assisted bicycles;
3 (B) Electric personal assistive mobility devices;
4 (C) Motor assisted scooters;
5 (D) Motorized wheelchairs;
6 (E) Motorcycles;
7 (F) Mopeds; or
8 (G) All-terrain vehicles.
9 SECTION 3. Application of vehicle laws to powered micromobility devices. (1) A powered
10 micromobility device is not a motor vehicle for purposes of the Oregon Vehicle Code, except
11 when specifically provided by statute.
12 (2) A person operating a powered micromobility device is subject to any provisions ap-
13 plicable to and has the same rights and duties as the driver of a bicycle, except when oth-
14 erwise specifically provided by statute.
15 (3) Subject to the provisions of subsections (1) and (2) of this section, for purposes of the
16 vehicle code:
17 (a) A powered micromobility device is a vehicle; and
18 (b) When the term “vehicle” is used the term shall be deemed to be applicable to powered
19 micromobility devices, except those provisions that by their very nature can have no appli-
20 cation to the devices.
21 (4) The provisions of the vehicle code relating to the operation of a powered micromo-
22 bility device do not relieve an operator or motorist from the duty to exercise due care.
23 SECTION 4. Local government and state agency regulation of the operation of powered
24 micromobility devices. Local governments and state agencies having jurisdiction over side-
25 walks and trails of public passage may regulate by ordinance or rule and by traffic control
26 device the time, place and manner of the operation of powered micromobility devices on
27 sidewalks and trails.
