15 PROTECTIVE HEADGEAR REQUIREMENTS
16
17 SECTION 13. ORS 814.486 is amended to read:
18 814.486. (1) A person commits the offense of endangering a [bicycle] vehicle operator or pas-
19 senger if:
20 (a) The person is operating or using a [bicycle] vehicle on a highway or on premises open to
21 the public and the person carries another person on the [bicycle] vehicle who is under 16 years of
22 age and is not wearing protective headgear of a type approved under ORS 815.052; or
23 (b) The person is the parent, legal guardian or person with legal responsibility for the safety
24 and welfare of a child under 16 years of age and the child operates, uses or rides on a [bicycle]
25 vehicle on a highway or on premises open to the public without wearing protective headgear of a
26 type approved under ORS 815.052.
27 [(2) Exemptions from this section are as provided in ORS 814.487.]
28 (2) This section applies to the following vehicles:
29 (a) Bicycles;
30 (b) Motor assisted scooters;
31 (c) Electric personal assistive mobility devices;
32 (d) Powered micromobility devices; or
33 (e) Skateboards, nonmotorized scooters or in-line skates.
34 (3) The offense described in this section, endangering a [bicycle] vehicle operator or passenger,
35 is a specific fine traffic violation. The presumptive fine for endangering a [bicycle] vehicle operator
36 or passenger is $25.
37 (4) The first time a person is convicted of an offense described in this section the person
38 is not required to pay a fine if the person proves to the satisfaction of the court that the
39 person has protective headgear of a type approved under ORS 815.052.
40 SECTION 14. ORS 814.489 is amended to read:
41 814.489. (1) Evidence of violation of ORS [814.485 or] 814.486 and evidence of lack of protective
42 headgear [shall] is not [be] admissible, applicable or effective to reduce the amount of damages or
43 to constitute a defense to an action for damages brought by or on behalf of an injured [bicyclist or
44 bicycle passenger] operator, user or passenger of a vehicle or the survivors of a deceased [bicyclist
45 or passenger] operator, user or passenger of a vehicle if the [bicyclist or passenger] operator,
[10]

HB 4007
1 user or passenger of a vehicle was injured or killed as a result in whole or in part of the fault
2 of another.
3 (2) For purposes of this section, “vehicle” means the vehicles specified in ORS 814.486 (2).
4 SECTION 15. ORS 815.052 is amended to read:
5 815.052. (1) The Department of Transportation shall adopt and enforce rules establishing mini-
6 mum standards and specifications for safe protective headgear to be worn by people operating, us-
7 ing, being carried on or riding [bicycles, by passengers on bicycles and by people riding on
8 skateboards or scooters or using in-line skates] vehicles.
9 (2) This section applies to the following vehicles:
10 (a) Bicycles;
11 (b) Motor assisted scooters;
12 (c) Electric personal assistive mobility devices;
13 (d) Powered micromobility devices; or
14 (e) Skateboards, nonmotorized scooters or in-line skates.
15 (3) The rules shall conform, insofar as practicable, to national safety standards and specifica-
16 tions for such headgear.
17 SECTION 16. ORS 815.281 is amended to read:
18 815.281. (1) A person commits the offense of selling noncomplying [bicycle] protective equipment
19 if the person sells or offers for sale any [bicycle] protective headgear that does not meet the stan-
20 dards established by the Department of Transportation under ORS 815.052.
21 (2) A person commits the offense of unlawfully renting or leasing a [bicycle] vehicle to another
22 if the person:
23 (a) Is in the business of renting or leasing [bicycles] vehicles; and
24 (b) Does not have [bicycle] protective headgear approved under ORS 815.052 available for rental
25 for use by persons under 16 years of age.
26 (3) The offenses described in this section are Class D traffic violations.
