32 MILK TRUCKS
33
34 SECTION 26. Section 27 of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of the Oregon Ve-
35 hicle Code.
36 SECTION 27. (1) The Department of Transportation shall establish a five-year pilot pro-
37 gram designed to test the allowance of commercial motor vehicles weighing not more than
38 129,000 pounds that transport fluid milk products on a limited number of highways in this
39 state. The department shall adopt rules specifying pilot program routes on highways in this
40 state where the department may issue permits for increased motor vehicle weights. In se-
41 lecting the routes, the department shall prioritize routes that utilize Interstate Highway 84
42 and:
43 (a) Connect to bordering states; and
44 (b) Connect to farms, milk plants, receiving stations or transfer stations for fluid milk
45 products.
[18]

HB 4007
1 (2) Notwithstanding ORS 818.010 and 818.020 and in addition to the exemptions allowed
2 under ORS 801.026 and 818.030, under the pilot program the department shall issue permits
3 that allow commercial motor vehicles hauling fluid milk products with a loaded weight of not
4 more than 129,000 pounds to operate on routes approved by the department.
5 (3) The department shall specify the conditions and terms of a permit issued under this
6 section.
7 (4) Applications for a permit under this section shall be made in a form and manner
8 prescribed by the department.
9 (5) The department, upon receiving satisfactory evidence of any violation of the limita-
10 tions of a permit issued under this section, may suspend or revoke the permit.
11 (6) The department shall periodically report back to the Oregon Transportation Com-
12 mission on the results of its monitoring and evaluation of impacts to safety, bridges and
13 pavement on all the designated routes within the pilot program.
14 (7) No later than September 15, 2032, the department shall prepare and submit a report
15 to the Joint Committee on Transportation and the commission on pilot program results. The
16 report must include:
17 (a) A comprehensive assessment on increasing maximum weight limitations under the
18 Oregon Vehicle Code;
19 (b) An infrastructure impact assessment detailing the effects of heavier vehicle weight
20 loads on bridges, pavement and highway safety, with a focus on high-frequency freight routes
21 in this state;
22 (c) An economic impact assessment quantifying the contributions of oversized freight to
23 Oregon’s economy, balancing potential economic gains from increased freight capacity with
24 the costs of infrastructure maintenance and safety considerations;
25 (d) An assessment of length as a factor for legal axle weights and alignment with lengths
26 allowed by the long combination vehicle freeze in federal law;
27 (e) An assessment of parking and staging infrastructure in this state for oversized loads;
28 and
29 (f) Recommendations supporting informed evaluation of increasing maximum vehicle
30 weight limits for divisible and nondivisible loads.
31 (8) The report described in subsection (7) of this section may include recommendations
32 for:
33 (a) Adjusting permit fees to account for highway maintenance needs;
34 (b) Identifying designated heavy-load corridors to minimize infrastructure impacts and
35 improve highway safety;
36 (c) Designating corridor connections to neighboring states that currently allow increased
37 vehicle weight limits for commercial motor vehicles as authorized under federal law;
38 (d) Updating the state transportation asset management plan;
39 (e) Changing weigh stations and weigh-in-motion systems;
40 (f) Adjusting bridge inspection plans and load-rating processes;
41 (g) Updating weight-mile tax rates and tables; and
42 (h) Collaborating with local road authorities.
43 (9) The department may adopt rules to carry out the provisions of this section.
44 SECTION 28. Section 27 of this 2026 Act is repealed on January 2, 2033.
